1328–1380":"1328–1380","1330–1380":"1330–1380","1354–1395":"1354–1395","1300–1360":"1300–1360","–Female":"Deceased","Abt 1354":"about 1354","1300":"1300","1354":"1354","about 1348":"about 1348","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","Abt 1328":"about 1328","before 1328":"before 1328","1328":"1328","Holway, Somerset, England":"Holway, Somerset, England","Holway, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Holway, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Holne, Devonshire, England":"Holne, Devon, England, United Kingdom","<Of Holway, Devonshire, Eng.>":"Holway, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Holway","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Donal, Patrick James.","English (Devon and Somerset): variant of   Holloway  , perhaps specifically from Holway in Somerset."],"variants":[{"name":"Holloway","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived ‘(by the) sunken road’, from Middle English <i>hol(g)h</i> ‘hollow’ + <i>weie</i> ‘way, road’ (Old English <i>holh</i> + <i>weg</i>), or else a habitational name from any of numerous places so named, such as Holloway (Middlesex) or Holway (Somerset). In Ireland (Leinster), the name has sometimes been Gaelicized as <b>Ó hAilmhic</b> (see   Hulvey  )."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Holway II was born about 1328, in Holway, Somerset, England, United Kingdom as the son of Robert de Holway I and Mrs Robert de Holway I. He married Margaret of Devonshire about 1348, in Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1380, in his hometown, at the age of 53."},"et":{"Abt 1328–1380":"umbes 1328–1380","1328–1380":"1328–1380","1330–1380":"1330–1380","1354–1395":"1354–1395","1300–1360":"1300–1360","–Female":"Surnud","Abt 1354":"umbes 1354","1300":"1300","1354":"1354","about 1348":"umbes 1348","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","Abt 1328":"umbes 1328","before 1328":"enne 1328","1328":"1328","Holway, Somerset, England":"Holway, Somerset, England","Holway, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Holway, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Holne, Devonshire, England":"Holne, Devon, Inglismaa, United Ki